          'UPS inverter voltage control loop: the output voltage is measured (sensed), compared to the voltage reference (setpoint = nominal output voltage). The error signal is processed by the controller (often a PI or PID controller), which adjusts the PWM duty cycle to drive the error toward zero. The loop operates at the switching frequency, responding within microseconds.',
          'PID controller in UPS: P (Proportional) — output correction proportional to current error. I (Integral) — correction accumulates based on persistent error — eliminates steady-state offset. D (Derivative) — anticipates future error based on rate of change — improves transient response. Proper PID tuning gives stable, fast voltage regulation without oscillation.',
